n preserves the fact that **your initial choice was wrong** with probability **2/3**.\n- When Monty removes one losing option among the two you didn’t choose, the entire remaining **2/3 probability mass** must concentrate on the one unopened door—so that door is the prize with probability **2/3**.\n\n---\n\n## Final result\n**Switching doors wins twice as often as staying.**\n- Switch ⇒ **2/3**\n- Stay ⇒ **1/3**\n\nIf you want, I can also show the same logic via a small probability table or by symmetry with conditional probabilities."}],"phase":"final_answer","role":"assistant"},"output_index":0,"sequence_number":579}

